# Spring Bean Scopes — Quick Notes

Bean scope defines **how many instances** of a bean Spring creates and **how long they live**.

---

## 1. Singleton (default)
- **Definition:** One instance per Spring container, shared everywhere.
- **Usage:** `@Scope("singleton")` or nothing (default).
- **Real-life use:** Stateless services — `ProductService`, `PaymentGateway`, `EmailService`.
- **Analogy:** One bank teller window serving all customers.

## 2. Prototype
- **Definition:** New instance every time the bean is requested.
- **Usage:** `@Scope("prototype")`
- **Real-life use:** Stateful, short-lived objects — `InvoiceGenerator`, `ReportBuilder`.
- **Analogy:** A fresh receipt pad for every new order.
- **Note:** Spring does NOT manage full lifecycle (no `@PreDestroy` callback).

## 3. Request *(web-aware)*
- **Definition:** New instance per HTTP request; dies when request ends.
- **Usage:**
  ```java
  @Scope(value = WebApplicationContext.SCOPE_REQUEST, proxyMode = ScopedProxyMode.TARGET_CLASS)
  ```
- **Real-life use:** Per-call metadata — `RequestAuditInfo` (request ID, IP, timestamp).
- **Analogy:** A visitor badge valid only for one visit.

## 4. Session *(web-aware)*
- **Definition:** New instance per HTTP session; persists across multiple requests until logout/timeout.
- **Usage:**
  ```java
  @Scope(value = WebApplicationContext.SCOPE_SESSION, proxyMode = ScopedProxyMode.TARGET_CLASS)
  ```
- **Real-life use:** User-specific data — `ShoppingCart`, `LoggedInUserProfile`.
- **Analogy:** A shopping trolley — yours for the whole visit, emptied after you leave.

## 5. Application *(web-aware)*
- **Definition:** One instance per `ServletContext` (shared across whole web app).
- **Real-life use:** Site-wide shared data — visitor counter, app-wide config cache.

## 6. WebSocket *(web-aware)*
- **Definition:** One instance per WebSocket session.
- **Real-life use:** Live features — chat session, real-time order tracking.

---

## Why `proxyMode` is needed
`request`/`session` beans are shorter-lived than the `singleton` beans (like Controllers) that inject them. Spring injects a **proxy** that delegates to the correct real instance at runtime, instead of failing at startup.

---

## Quick Comparison Table

| Scope | New Instance When | Lives Until | Example Bean |
|---|---|---|---|
| singleton | Once (container startup) | Container shuts down | ProductService |
| prototype | Every `getBean()` call | Caller discards it | InvoiceGenerator |
| request | Every HTTP request | Request completes | RequestAuditInfo |
| session | Every HTTP session | Session ends/logout | ShoppingCart |
| application | Once per ServletContext | App shuts down | VisitorCounter |
| websocket | Every WebSocket session | Socket closes | ChatSession |

---

## Rule of Thumb
1. No state held → **singleton**
2. Needs isolated state per creation → **prototype**
3. State relevant to one HTTP call only → **request**
4. State relevant to one user across calls → **session**
